<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOUTH BAY DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: NO-SMOKING LAW DRAFTED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Smoking will be banned in city-owned buildings and public areas of banks, 
restaurants and other establishments under a new law drafted by El Segundo 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
Council members are expected to adopt the ordinance when they meet May 16. It 
will go into effect 30 days later. 
</P>
<P>
City regulations will follow those advocated by Americans for Non-Smokers 
Rights, which lobbied council members to draft the ordinance. 
</P>
<P>
Besides prohibiting smoking in city buildings and public areas, the ordinance 
will require restaurants with more than 40 seats to create a nonsmoking area. 
Eateries with fewer than 40 seats will be required to post a sign telling 
customers whether smoking is allowed or prohibited. 
</P>
<P>
Also, employers must maintain nonsmoking areas in lounges and cafeterias, and 
establish smoke-free areas for nonsmokers "to the maximum extent possible." 
Employers will not be forced to create smoke-free areas if it requires them to 
incur any expenses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
